# Key Findings — Netflix Content Analysis

**Analyst:** Santi Aulia Dewi  
**Dataset:** Netflix Movies and TV Shows (Kaggle)  
**Total Titles Analyzed:** 8,807  
**Period Covered:** 2008 – 2021  

---

## 1. Content Type Distribution

| Type | Total | Percentage |
|------|-------|------------|
| Movies | 6,131 | 69.6% |
| TV Shows | 2,676 | 30.4% |

**Finding:** Netflix is predominantly a movie platform — nearly 7 out of 10 titles are movies. However, TV Shows have been growing faster in recent years as Netflix invests more in original series.

---

## 2. Average Content Duration

| Type | Average Duration |
|------|-----------------|
| Movies | 99 minutes |
| TV Shows (most common) | 1 Season |

**Finding:** Most Netflix movies run around 90–100 minutes — standard feature film length. The majority of TV Shows have only 1 season, suggesting many are either limited series or cancelled after one season.

---

## 3. Top 10 Content-Producing Countries

| Rank | Country | Titles |
|------|---------|--------|
| 1 | United States | 3,690 |
| 2 | India | 1,046 |
| 3 | United Kingdom | 806 |
| 4 | Japan | 395 |
| 5 | South Korea | 301 |
| 6 | Canada | 281 |
| 7 | Spain | 235 |
| 8 | France | 224 |
| 9 | Mexico | 110 |
| 10 | Australia | 97 |

**Finding:** The US dominates Netflix content with 42% of all titles. India ranks second, reflecting Netflix's heavy investment in Bollywood and regional Indian content. South Korea's presence (rank 5) is notable given the global rise of K-Drama and K-content.

---

## 4. Yearly Content Trends

| Year | Titles Added | YoY Growth |
|------|-------------|------------|
| 2016 | 1,030 | — |
| 2017 | 1,788 | +73.6% |
| 2018 | 1,960 | +9.6% |
| 2019 | 2,153 | +9.8% |
| 2020 | 1,879 | -12.7% |
| 2021 | 1,498 | -20.3% |

**Finding:** Netflix's content additions peaked in 2019. The decline in 2020–2021 is likely due to COVID-19 disrupting global film and TV production schedules. The sharp growth in 2017 reflects Netflix's major push into original content.

